{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"1286b1fd-a66c-4cac-a272-9eb2d7783029","content":"I can help guide you through analyzing your crash dump. The `dump-collect` skill I have available is specifically for **collecting** dumps, not analyzing them — so let me give you direct guidance instead.\n\n### Analyzing a .NET crash dump\n\nUse **`dotnet-dump analyze`** (cross-platform) or **WinDbg/lldb** depending on your OS:\n\n```bash\n# Install the tool if needed\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-dump\n\n# Open the dump\ndotnet-dump analyze your-app.dmp\n```\n\nOnce inside the interactive session, run these commands in order:\n\n| Command | Purpose |\n|---|---|\n| `printexception` / `pe` | Show the last exception |\n| `clrstack` | Managed call stack for current thread |\n| `clrthreads` | List all managed threads |\n| `dumpheap -stat` | Heap summary (useful for OOM) |\n| `setthread <id>` + `pe` | Check exceptions on other threads |\n\n### Quick triage flow\n\n1. **`pe -nested`** — shows the exception chain (including inner exceptions)  \n2. **`clrstack`** — see where it crashed  \n3. **`clrthreads`** — look for threads with non-zero exception addresses  \n4. Inspect suspicious threads with `setthread <id>`, then `pe` and `clrstack`\n\nWould you like help running any of these commands on your dump file, or do you need guidance on a specific crash symptom (e.g., `StackOverflow`, `AccessViolation`, `OutOfMemoryException`)?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"8ac09255-a9eb-4ba4-a106-0e616ed229cf","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about analyzing a .dmp crash dump file. Let me check the available skills - there's a `dump-collect` skill, but its description explicitly says \"DO NOT USE FOR: analyzing or debugging dumps, post-mortem investigation with lldb/windbg/dotnet-dump analyze.\" So that skill is not appropriate here.\n\nI should help the user directly with guidance on analyzing crash dumps.","outputTokens":483,"requestId":"D822:1E62:29D60B6:2E38